<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=3&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;3</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=5&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;5&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_4.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_4.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>OPERATION WOLF</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>21 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
I only started reading computer magazines in the Summer of 1987, so
when 1988 came around I was still fresh to the idea of hype, the
annual cycle, and the sheer shininess of everything to notice that the
run-up to Christmas 1988 was going to be very special indeed.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d4_1988_ad3.png" target="1988_ad3.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d4_1988_ad3_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=296></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Where would we be without teasers in the run-up to Christmas?</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE><i>Operation Wolf</i> had hit the arcades with huge success as it was the
first shooting gallery game to do the genre any justice, with six
mini-missions, sharp graphics and a massive Uzi machine gun attached
to the front of the machine. Of course I was a crap aim, so I was
reduced to watching others blasting away at the bad guys before
forgetting about the game entirely.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d4_1988_ad8.png" target="1988_ad8.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d4_1988_ad8_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=213></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>The rarely-seen <i>Op Wolf</i> double-page ad.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/zFHS1OkFfwc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/zFHS1OkFfwc&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>1988 telly ads, including some favourites!</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">How very '80s! Our Price (ad for a house music compilation), Martini Extra Dry, the Bad album, useless gizmos and many more! <b><i>(7:18)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zFHS1OkFfwc" target="zFHS1OkFfwc">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
Then Spring arrived. Spring. Christmas was barely a thought in my mind
and yet here was Sinclair User with a double-page spread for <i>Operation
Wolf</i>. With typical SU accuracy, it promised a June release date and I
was immediately put onto red alert keeping an eye out for any more
information about the game. This game genre hadn't really appeared on
the Spectrum before and I'm always a sucker for well-executed new
ideas.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=290 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="280" height="170"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/E8gmARGvPlI&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/E8gmARGvPlI&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="280" height="170"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Last Christmas / Wham!</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Ahhh, memories of school Christmas parties come flooding back. Did you know that this has been covered by various teen pop acts since? Search YouTube and prepare to vomit. <b><i>(4:38)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E8gmARGvPlI" target="E8gmARGvPlI">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
The year dragged on. The other mags eventually caught up with SU in
the Summer, more screenshots and more hype. Looking back I can only
guess at the delay from June to November or December. The best I can
come up with is that the 16-bit games scene was starting to heat up.
Whilst the &pound;25 games weren't getting cheaper, the computers which run
them certainly were. A new market was opening up for the software
houses and it might have made sense for Ocean to hold back the 8-bit
releases of <i>Op Wolf</i> until the Atari ST and Commodore Amiga versions
were done - that could have filled in that six-month gap quite nicely.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/FqwMt9uWHEo&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/FqwMt9uWHEo&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>SU Operation Wolf Demo</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">The first demo I saw which put in a time-out on the gameplay. Which makes sense, as it was just a six-stage shooting gallery game. <b><i>(1:30)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FqwMt9uWHEo" target="FqwMt9uWHEo">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
So, Speccy owners like myself waited. SU then scooped the other mags
again by getting a playable demo onto their October issue. It was a
bit of an oddity - due to the game itself being rather basic in design
(it really was just shoot everything that moved), it was the first
<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=300 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d4_1988_rev1.png" target="1988_rev1.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d4_1988_rev1_small.jpg" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=215></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Instant classic, and you can see YS was experimenting with backgrounds which made articles a little unreadable...</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
playable demo I had seen which had a short time limit: just enough to
get a flavour of the game, but not enough to spoil the chances of
anyone buying the finished product as the demo might have been enough
for them.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;When the game was finally released in December, it was a monster hit -
the Christmas #2 and it charted well throughout 1989. One of Ocean's
finest.
</TD></TR></TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
